{"type":"message","id":"85e0ba9f","parentId":"8cb73121","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:35:35.214Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_fvmrs7ykas4w_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 103317\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI-COMPRESSION-EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine a concrete action for this pulse.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals and recent findings:\r\n\r\n1. Phase 0 and Phase 1 are complete\r\n2. CFI Analysis has been completed with key findings about frequency invariants\r\n3. The next pending action is: \"CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\"\r\n\r\nThis is explicitly listed as the next action to take. The CFI_RESULTS.md shows that:\r\n- 44.8% have CFI=0 (pure noise/metaprogramming artifacts)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181 - frequency-based compression is mostly signal loss\r\n\r\nSo the logical next step is to implement a CFI-weighted compression experiment. I should create an experiment that:\r\n1. Compares CFI-weighted prediction vs frequency-only baseline\r\n2. Tests next-pulse prediction accuracy\r\n\r\nLet me look at what files exist that I could build upon. I need to find the pulse data or some invariant data to work with.\r\n\r\nI should create an experiment script or document that tests CFI-weighted compression. Let me check what pulse files exist or what data I can analyze.\r\n\r\nThe CFI_RESULTS.md is at `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`. Let me look at what data was analyzed there - it likely has the invariant data I need to work with.\r\n\r\nMy concrete action: Create a CFI-weighted compression experiment that compares prediction accuracy vs frequency baseline. This could be a Python script or PowerShell script that:\r\n1. Loads the invariant analysis data\r\n2. Implements both frequency-weighted and CFI-weighted compression\r\n3. Compares prediction accuracy for next-pulse content\r\n\r\nLet me create a focused experiment script.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that frequency-based compression loses ~82% of signal (mean CFI=0.181). The next logical step is to test whether CFI-weighted compression improves next-pulse prediction accuracy versus the frequency-only baseline.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate `research/cfi_compression_experiment.md` with an experiment design to compare CFI-weighted vs frequency-only compression for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```markdown\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24  \r\n**Status:** Design Phase\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only compression for next-pulse prediction because it filters out metaprogramming artifacts (CFI=0) while preserving true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7).\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Variables\r\n- **Independent:** Compression method (frequency-only vs CFI-weighted)\r\n- **Dependent:** Next-pulse prediction accuracy (% of actual next-pulse content covered)\r\n- **Control:** Training pulse count, vocabulary size\r\n\r\n### Data Source\r\n- Pulse invariants from `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n- Historical pulse files: `pulse_*.md`\r\n\r\n### Method\r\n\r\n#### Baseline: Frequency-Only Compression\r\n```python\r\n# Pseudocode\r\ndef frequency_compress(pulses, k):\r\n    invariants = extract_invariants(pulses)\r\n    ranked = sort_by_frequency(invariants)\r\n    return ranked[:k]  # Top-k by frequency\r\n```\r\n\r\n#### Treatment: CFI-Weighted Compression\r\n```python\r\n# Pseudocode\r\ndef cfi_compress(pulses, k):\r\n    invariants = extract_invariants(pulses)\r\n    # Filter: CFI > 0 (remove pure noise)\r\n    # Weight: CFI * log(frequency) to balance persistence with recency\r\n    weighted = [(cfi * math.log(freq), text) for text, freq, cfi in invariants]\r\n    ranked = sort_by_weight(weighted)\r\n    return ranked[:k]\r\n```\r\n\r\n#### Evaluation\r\nFor each pulse `P[i]`, predict content for `P[i+1]` using:\r\n- Compression from pulses `P[0..i-1]`\r\n- Measure: Jaccard similarity with actual `P[i+1]` content\r\n\r\n### Expected Outcome\r\n| Method | Prediction Coverage |\r\n|--------|-------------------|\r\n| Frequency-only | ~18% (baseline from CFI analysis) |\r\n| CFI-weighted | >18% (target: >40%) |\r\n\r\n## Implementation Plan\r\n1. [ ] Parse pulse files into invariant corpus\r\n2. [ ] Implement frequency-only compressor\r\n3. [ ] Implement CFI-weighted compressor  \r\n4. [ ] Run comparison across all pulse pairs\r\n5. [ ] Generate statistical summary\r\n\r\n## Files\r\n- Script: `scripts/cfi_experiment.py`\r\n- Results: `research/CFI_EXPERIMENT_RESULTS.md`\r\nfile: research/cfi_compression_experiment.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:33:49\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774362935210}}
